RESULTS

WOMEN (FINAL): Karnataka (Aadhya Gowda 16, Adhya Nagalinga 16, Aditi Subraminiam 12) bt Punjab (Chanda Gouttam 20, Nadar Dhillon 15, Komalpreet Kaur 12) 71-51 (14-11, 19-12, 18-11, 20-17);

THIRD PLACE: Maharashtra (Gunjan Mantri 16, Aanaya Bhavsar 15, Muskan Singh 15, Rajvi Maladhari 7) bt Madhya Pradesh (Gunvi Agrawal 16, Ananya Maheshwari 15) 69-66 (18-17, 24-24, 13-11, 14-14);

MEN (FINAL): Rajasthan (Nitesh Kumar 28, Ajay Kumar 27, Mayank Jawa 19, Mohammad Ishan 12) bt Chandigarh (Gaurav Kumar Singh 22, Om SItta Prangya 10) 107-49 (25-14, 19-7, 30-15, 33-13);

THIRD PLACE: Madhya Pradesh (Rohan Sejwal 26, Kirtiraj Chandrawat 16) bt Uttar Pradesh (Harshit Tomar 17) 71-49 (12-16, 30-7, 16-13, 13-13).

INDORE: Karnataka women and Rajasthan men kept their best for the last and emerged as the new junior national basketball champions in the 74th edition of the meet which concluded at the Emerald Heights International School in Indore on Tuesday.After taking early lead both Karnataka and Rajasthan stretched their advantage further to lift the women and men titles in style.While Karnataka utilized their speed well to prevail over Punjab by 20 points (71-51), the lanky lads from Rajasthan thrashed Chandigarh 107-49.The only exciting clash of the concluding day was the bronze medal game between Maharashtra and Madhya Pradesh women, where the visitors defeated hosts 69-66. The men’s bronze medal game too was a lop-sided affair where MP outclassed defending champions Uttar Pradesh 71-49.In the women’s title clash, Karnataka made the most of their speed and gave a near-perfect shooting display to take Punjab in their stride. After winning the first quarter 14-11, Karnataka stretched the advantage further to 10 points by winning the second period 19-12. After the change of ends, Karnataka continued to keep control of the proceedings and won the third and fourth periods 18-11 and 20-17 to pocket the title in style.Despite being low on height, Karnataka blocked the lanky Punjab girls by winning the battle of boards 55-45 and displayed their speed by scoring as many as 16 fast-break points as against the four netted by their opponents.Karnataka skipper Adhya Nagalinga and post guard Aadhya Gowda netted identical 16 points as their semifinalist show stopper and 15-year-old shooting guard Aditi Subraminiam contributed 12 points. For Punjab, Chanda Gouttam (20), Nadar Dhillon (15) and Komalpreet Kaur (12) played well.Karnataka coach Satyanarayana K was on top of the world. “Ours was a normal team in this championship. We never expected to clinch the title. The 40-point drubbing that we had against Tamil Nadu in our tournament opener was the turning point as the girls became determined to give their best. Though we lost the second game closely, we played much better and became confident. We acted according to the situation and got the desired results and are more than happy to go home with the gold,” Satyanarayana told TOI.Much like the women’s final, the men’s title clash between Rajasthan and Chandigarh was a lop-sided affair. Rajasthan utilized their height well to dominate the final by as many as 58 points (107-49).After winning the first quarter 25-14, Rajasthan dominated the second period 19-7 to take a handy 23-point lead at the breather. Rajasthan continued their dominance after the lemon break and gave no chance for Chandigarh to recover.While their tallest centre Mohammad Ishan scored a double double with 12 points and 20 rebounds, Rajasthan’s shooting guards Nitesh Kumar (28), Ajay Kumar (27) and Mayank Jawa (19) did the bulk of the scoring. For Chandigarh, Gaurav Kumar Singh (22) and Om Sitta Prangya (10) scored in double digits. Rajasthan outrebounded Chandigarh 65-34.The thrilling tie of the concluding day was the battle of two tournament favourites Maharashtra and hosts Madhya Pradesh, who ended up playing the bronze medal game after both went down fighting in their semifinals. Maharashtra handled the pressure well to win the battle of nerves by three points (69-66).For the winners, Gunjan Mantri (16), Muskan Singh (15), Aanaya Bhavsar (15) and Rajvi Maladhari (7) played well while Madhya Pradesh’s Gunvi Agrawal (16) and Ananya Maheshwari (15) were the notable scorers.
